	<td bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	<td class="subjectbar" height="20" style="font-size: 8pt;padding-left:10px;" width="100%">
		Re: How to Fix EQ PvP - Address the real issue

	</td>
	
		<td class="subjectbar" align=right style="padding:0px;padding-right:10px;">












		<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0 id="io_bpvpm440_table" 
		
			onClick="setId('440');showLiMenu(this,'io_bpvpm440','right',false);" 
			onDblClick="setId('440');showLiMenu(this,'io_bpvpm440','right',false);" 
			
		>
		<tr class=clickable>
			
				<td nowrap><a class=subjectbar_text style='font-size: 8pt;'>Options</a></td>
				
			<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
			<td><img src='/i/skins/default/button_options.gif' border=0 alt='Options' title='Options' width=11 height=28></td>
			<td>&nbsp;</td></tr>
		</table>
		
		</td></tr>
		
	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=26059'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#336600;'>Tweadledumm</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Journeyman<br>
			
				Posts: 84<br>
				
				Registered: 04-16-2004
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=26059'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=PVP&message.id=440#M440">57</a> of 127
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 484 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		
				background-color: #050A0E; 
				
				 background-image: none;
				 
				background-repeat: repeat-x;
				" 
			>
			<P>Try AC darktide, you'll know what PvP should be like.&nbsp; Here's some examples, oh and I'll say upfront that EQ will never be able to implment such PvP system due to limitations and how the game is designed.</P>
<P>1) Death -&nbsp;you don't lose exp, and in turn you never lose level of course.&nbsp; Nobody wants to worry about losing exp when PvP'ing, nobody wants to have to worry about losing levels.&nbsp; It's not fun, it sucks, and it's not needed.&nbsp; What happens when you die in AC is that you get a penalty slapped on you.&nbsp; The penalty is reduced stats and reduced HP/Mana.&nbsp;&nbsp; This penalty stays on you until you work it off by killing a few monsters.&nbsp; In another words, the death penalty only goes away if you gain enough exp to get rid of it.</P>
<P>And each time you die, you gain 5% death penalty.&nbsp; AC had it set so that you can gain a maximum of 40% penalty, which means you can not die so much to make your stats 0 hehe.&nbsp; This is good because well, there's a cap so you can't totally destroy your character.&nbsp; Also if you do have a 40% penalty on yourself, you are better off heading to gain some exp to work it off rather than PvP because your ability to PvP gets reduced.&nbsp; It doesn't make you useless however, so when you are in an epic battle and somehow got yourself killed 10 times in a row, you can still do little things to help out if you refuse to head out.</P>
<P>Also right after you die, when you are naked, you are invulnerable for about&nbsp;15-20 seconds.&nbsp; This kind of gives you time to get away or port away in case someone happens to be bound to the same life stone that you are bound to.&nbsp; There are no instant gates, no books people can insta click away.&nbsp; Sure sometimes people play portal tag with you, but AC is smart enough to put where people pop in a new zone quite a few steps away from the zone itself.&nbsp; The only place you are safe is inside your house, and well, you are often far far away from your house heh.</P>
<P>2) Death/Loots - Yes there are item loots in AC.&nbsp; If you can't loot someone, what's the point to PvP?&nbsp; If you don't have to worry about losing items, why would you try so hard not to die?&nbsp; Depending on your level, the higher level you are, the more items you drop each time you die.&nbsp; However, it's not how you think like in EQ, you really don't have a lot of items you carry that you can drop.&nbsp; But in AC, there are "death items" you can collect.&nbsp; They are simply loots that have high values on them.&nbsp; You see, in AC they tag every items with a money value on them.&nbsp; So if you wear a full set of armor that have a highest value of 5,000 on them for an example, you can carry 10,000 value items on you.&nbsp; So when you die, 10,000 value items will drop first rather than your armors/weapons.&nbsp; If you run out of items to drop, you better head out to kill a few mobs to collect more high value items.&nbsp; This system is a self contained system, because an economy is created where low value items are VERY valuable to people since if you can wear value 1,000 items for an example, you only have to carry items that are worth around 3,000.&nbsp; Versus someone wearing a suit valuing around 5,000, they have to carry higher value items to drop.</P>
<P>This system may sound weird in EQ, of course, ,EQ isn't designed like this. First of all, EQ items do not have values tagged on them.&nbsp; Second, mobs really don't drop enough loot for this system to work.&nbsp; In AC however, mobs drop a lot of loot, each loot varying in values.&nbsp; So this cycle of losing and gaining death items isn't as bad as it sounds.&nbsp; Also, this system is what makes the PvP so fun and awesome.&nbsp; When you kill someone, you get to loot their body and see what they drop.&nbsp; If they carry high value Death Items, hey you collect items for yourself that you can carry as death items, or sell for money.&nbsp; If someone did not carry enough death items to cover everything they wear/use, you may sometimes find a very nice piece of armor or weapon that would drop off someone's body.&nbsp; So PvP is rewarding, which makes it fun.</P>
<P>3) Class balance - In EQ you play characters that are pre-designed already. You gain stats by wearing certain equipments, and that's all you do.&nbsp; You have no control over your character's ability really.&nbsp; In AC, you totally customize your own character.&nbsp; There are no pre-designed "classes".&nbsp; You put points in where you want to specialize in.&nbsp; How fast you run for an example, has to do with how many points you put into the skill Run.&nbsp; How much damage you do with a dagger for an example, has to do with how many points you put into the skill Dagger, as well as attributes like Dex and Str.&nbsp; You want to be like a wizard that specialize in casting war magic?&nbsp; Put points into war magic, and you will be allow to use higher damage magic spells.&nbsp; Each character is unique to how you create them, and you can solo because you can make a well rounded character that can melee and heal yourself.&nbsp; Sometimes you'll find someone who is an "extreme sword melee" for an example, that just means that the person put a lot of points into sword, therefor you know he's lacking in probably the magic area and maybe he can't heal himself.&nbsp; But you better watch out for the guy with that big sword standing next to you, he'll hit damn hard.</P>
<P>4) Freedom of movements - In EQ, when someone casts a spell, you can either take it, resist it, or try to run out of range.&nbsp; In AC, when war mages cast war magic, you actually have to dodge it.&nbsp; When archers shoot arrows at you, you can see arrows and you can dodge it.&nbsp; Yes you actually have the freedom to move around, kinda like playing Quake.&nbsp; So imagine 2 war mages going at each other, the person that can time it and dodge the best probably wins.&nbsp; Of course resists factor into it as well, plus how much they've put points into war magic.&nbsp; So there's more freedom of movement, and skills are highly encouraged.&nbsp; You do get rewarded for your skill.&nbsp; In EQ however, whether a ranger's arrow hits you really depends on chance.&nbsp; They've gimped it so much it's not funny, and you can't really see the arrows either.&nbsp; Whether a wizard can land the nuke on you depends on your resist mostly, you don't exactly "dodge" a wizard's nuke.&nbsp; You are just too limited.</P>
<P>------</P>
<P>Anyways, I don't know why I went into explaining about AC, but I think AC has the best PvP system, and EQ PvP has always been considered "gimp pvp" by many others because of how limited you are.&nbsp; When you have to play pre-designed classes, you are in the hands of the developers.&nbsp; Unfortunately SOE has decided to not put much effort into EQ PvP, that's how we ended up with such gimpy pvp system.&nbsp; It doesn't matter how hard you try, or how much skill you have.&nbsp; When you come up against a team of SK's, Necros, and Wizards, you might as well lay down and die.&nbsp; </P>
<P>I think the only thing EQ can probably fix is class balance issues, and just let players play it out.&nbsp; EQ PvP is kinda doomed so people really shouldn't expect too much out of SOE at this time in game.&nbsp; Limiting on the level people can PvP only drives people away from trying PvP out.&nbsp; Having safe zones, instant gate, and books do nothing but harm the PvP environment.&nbsp; I guess you can tell that SOE cared nothing about PvP when PoP came out.</P>
<DIV></DIV>	
		</td></tr>
