		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			To get more precise on reists in PvP I would suggest an "exponential" resist system.<br>I will give an example:<br><br>Spell X resist check vs Magic<br>-----------------------------<br>0-100 MR -> normal count -> 100 MR max eff MR<br>101-200 MR -> 60% count -> 160 MR max eff MR<br>201-300 MR -> 40% count -> 200 MR max eff MR<br>301+ MR -> 20% count...<br><br>Also there should be a minimum chance for every spell to land (for damage spells maybe to do full or at least half max damage).<br><br>Lets say spell X has 15% minimum chance to stick and additionally the now improved chance to stick due to lowered effective resists for example. This would make several magic based spells more valuable.<br><br>In the end it will prolly come down to how easy to code/implement such changes are.<br>But generally I find exponential systems the best solution since they still give the hardcore gamer an advantage but give also the casual player a chance. For sure it would not be a bad Idea to have different minimum stick chances for each spell and also for each class. Generally pure melees should have a lesser minimal stick chance then hybrids and casters and maybe even an "temp invul to spells PvP skill 'focus of mind'" to compensate the lack of spells they have. If such a system would be implementeable that would also make it possible to make some classes more vulnerable to others as I suggested in my other post.<br><br>Sure such changes would need excessive testing but I think they could solve some of the issues in PvP.	
		</td></tr>
		<tr>
		
